A New Science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to think about the necessity of a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
In view of the great challenges, it is believed that there is not much left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: first, the major unresolved scientific puzzles (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a single theory), the research of which requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Second, data collection, referring to work connected with archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies; and third, problems whose solutions must be based on scientific principles, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Moreover, in many places, people believe that the only difficult part of the work would be to use already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny that?
The models of today do work, after all.
However, an increasing group of scientists points to phenomena that are not well explained by current theories.
These problems do occur more and more frequently, but they are also cleverly circumvented because the science that would be needed to explain them simply does not exist.
This lack of science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
Within the individual scientific disciplines, the knowledge is fairly well established.
Physics, at least the part with which we as ordinary people are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also rest on solid foundations — although there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, it can be assumed that the fundamental mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
In addition, there are the new social sciences, which focus on people and societies.
In each of these areas – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and largely beyond dispute.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest cases, a scientist is an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are simply so different.
That means we are unable to find answers to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
For example, think of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interactions occur based on the principles of physics. The information conveyed in this process is transmitted according to the laws of electricity.
In addition, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and also transmit information in this way.
In the interaction between two brains, a new level is added: Here, the exchange of information takes place through language, signs, and representations.
At every level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are suitable theories that explain the processes on each individual level.
Information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this exchange of information.
To compensate for this deficiency, some scientists have tried to redefine the framework for explaining processes within a level in order to then apply it on another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works quite well, but the fundamental problem is not solved by it: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the individual levels, and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this shameful lack of knowledge about how the entire system works.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who met in Paris has loosely formed itself under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from different countries and disciplines and have been working together in a decentralized manner for eight years.
In addition to scientists from the relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discussion.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," in which the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and transferred to another.
Others, on the other hand, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
In your view, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are necessary.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches may emerge from scientists who currently do not have access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Completely free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Almost all activities taking place under the sign of "science" have, like their counterparts in the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries must build up similar resources as industrialized countries. This could, however, stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these—sometimes revolutionary—ideas come from laboratories and research centers that are not associated with the major institutions.
The most sophisticated approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came from the Soviet Union for twenty years, where computer capacity was lacking everywhere.
The most brilliant and, in the truest sense of the word, world-changing insights in the field of physics in recent decades did not, as expected, come from the well-known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is an architectural tradition that has provided cognitive scientists with important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (so-called "autonomous agents") today come from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements went down in history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, the identity of space and time changed accordingly. The FIS conference in July was the unexpected beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this new way.
Those gaps were identified for which explanations must be found.
More scientists from innovative regions will be added to this group in order to then identify those problems that could be solved once this new science has been developed, or discovered, so to speak.
